Disabled regression test for issue #1081: a `cast` whose operand contains an undefined symbol can drive the IL emitter into a "generated dummy value" internal compiler error rather than reporting the underlying symbol-not-found at semantic time.

Currently:

```
test.ghul: 12,41..12,78: fatal: generated dummy value: Test.FOO from test.ghul 12,41..12,77
internal compiler error
```

Root cause: the symbol-not-found diagnostic fires inside a deeply-nested speculation level (call/binary overload speculate_then_backtrack chain). The constraint-push retry in `_visit(call)` rolls back that level — discarding overload-rejection noise but also discarding fundamental errors like "symbol not found" emitted from sub-walks of the receiver. With no error visible at top level, IL generation runs anyway and trips the DUMMY guard.

Tier A's `generate_il_pass` gate skips IL generation when prior errors are visible, which catches most cast-of-error patterns. This specific test still produces the FATAL because the underlying symbol-not-found is suppressed before IL gen runs — fixing that needs a way to preserve fundamental errors across speculation backtrack, which is a larger change.

Re-enable when the speculation rollback preserves fundamental (symbol-not-found / non-rejection) errors, or when the cast resolution can detect a poisoned operand and emit its own clear diagnostic without depending on the inner error surfacing.
